The Telegraph - Calcutta : Opinion
		 Monday, August 02, 2004 							 																						CARDINAL VIRTUES																														The Vaticans views on contraception and abortion, and on homosexuality are directly premised on these fundamental pieties. A document called Cherishing Life, issued by the Vatican in May, also outlined a personal morality, the language of which was so moralistic that the Catholic Church of England and Wales had decided to tone it down for the its use. The pope has recently canonized Gianna Beretta Molla for refusing cancer treatment and dying, so that her fourth child could be born. John Paul II has praised her extreme sacrifice, seeing her as embodying the pure, chaste and fertile beauty of conjugal love. However, the pope seems to accept the existence of working women, but asks governments to create conditions that enable women not to neglect their family duties when they go out to work.
